Program Intention :
===============================================================================================
This program uses xcalloc() like malloc( ), but zeros memory and terminates on failure

===============================================================================================
COMPILE :
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg267_xcalloc$ make
gcc -Wall -g -o pg267_xcalloc pg267_xcalloc.c;


===============================================================================================
Execution:
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg267_xcalloc$ ./pg267_xcalloc 

 Successfull xcalloc() 
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg267_xcalloc$ 


===============================================================================================
Program Flow
===============================================================================================
        use of  malloc() wrapper that prints an error message and terminates the program if
        malloc( ) returns NULL .
        By convention, developers call this common wrapper xmalloc( )





